# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: french-ship-napoléon-1850
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The **8×50mmR Lebel** (8mm Lebel) (designated as the **8 × 51 R Lebel** by the C.I.P.) rifle cartridge was the first smokeless powder cartridge to be made and adopted by any country.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11×59mmR Gras black powder cartridge, the smokeless 8mm Lebel cartridge started a revolution in military rifle ammunition.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Standard 8mm Lebel military ammunition was also the first rifle ammunition to feature a spitzer boat tail bullet (*balle* D), which was adopted in 1898.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The long-range ballistic performance of the 8mm Lebel bullet itself was exceptional for its time.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] For use in the magazine tube-fed early Lebel rifle, the 8 mm case was designed to protect against accidental percussion inside the tube magazine by a circular groove around the primer cup which caught the tip of the following pointed bullet.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] However, the shape of its rimmed bottle-necked case, having been designed for the Lebel rifle's tube magazine, also precluded truly efficient vertical stacking inside a vertical magazine.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The bolt thrust of the 8mm Lebel is relatively high compared to many other service rounds used in the early 20th century.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Although it was once revolutionary, the 8mm Lebel was declared obsolete after World War I and was soon after replaced with the 7.5×54mm French round.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] There were two historical commercially available 8mm Lebel cartridges: one for the Lebel Model 1886 rifle, and one for the Modèle 1892 revolver.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] They are two entirely different cartridges and are not interchangeable.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The term "8mm Lebel" for the French Mle 1892 revolver ammunition, is only applied outside France for commercial reasons and has nothing to do with the Lebel rifle.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] However, the term "8mm Lebel", used to identify a rifle cartridge, is widely recognized to distinguish the French rifle cartridge from other 8 mm rifle cartridges, such as the 8×50mmR Mannlicher cartridge used by Austria-Hungary and its successor states.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The cartridge for the tube-fed long arm was originally loaded with a 15.0 g (232 grains) cupro-nickel-jacketed, lead-cored, flat-nosed, wadcutter-style bullet, called "*balle M*", which had been designed by Lieutenant Colonel Nicolas Lebel.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The flat point (flat nose or tip) of this bullet had been designed to be safe inside the newly commissioned rifle's tube magazine.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] It was propelled by the first practical smokeless, nitrocellulose-based powder (*Poudre B*), as developed by Paul Vieille in 1884.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The ballistic performance and range of *balle M* with the new propellant eclipsed all the previous military ammunitions in existence at the time (1886).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] This *balle M* was replaced in 1898 by a new design, a 12.8 g (198 grains) 90/10 bronze mono-metal, pointed (spitzer) boat-tail bullet called "*balle D*", which provided a flatter trajectory and improved long-range performance.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Designed at the Atelier de Puteaux (APX) by Captain Georges Desaleux, the *balle D* was the first pointed *and* boat-tailed bullet to be placed into service by any military.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Later on in 1912, the round was improved into the *balle D am* ("am" stands for "*amorçage modifié*" or "modified primer"), done by crimping the primer in more deeply to prevent primer expulsions when fired in machine guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] This ammunition was in near-universal service during World War I (1914–1918) in all Lebel-caliber weapons.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The *balle D am* ammunition was followed in 1932 by *balle N* ammunition, which featured a lead-cored, cupro-nickel-over-steel-jacketed, pointed boat-tail bullet weighing 15.0 g (232 grains).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] It was thicker (8.3 mm instead of 8.17) and was held into a case that had a slightly larger neck diameter than that for the older *balle D am* ammunition.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The new *balle N* was again heavier than the *balle D am*, and had been designed to improve the long-range performance of the issued Hotchkiss machine guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Rechambering practically all French Lebel-caliber rifles and carbines to use the "N"-type ammunition was carried out during the 1930s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] A *balle T* (tracer ammunition) and *balle P* armor-piercing rounds were also produced, along with blank and reduced charge cartridges.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] In order to safely accommodate pointed (spitzer) bullets inside the Lebel rifle magazine, a circular groove was machined around each primer cup at the case base on both *balle D am* and *balle N* ammunitions.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The role of that circular groove is to receive the pointed bullet tip of the following round loaded inside the tube magazine, and keep it *at the side* of the case base of the previous cartridge, so the tip does not easily slide to the base center where the primer is located.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The tapered form of the case itself did help too to keep pointed tips away from the primer cup of a round in front of another in the tube.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Furthermore, all *balle D* and *balle M* French military ammunitions featured *convex primer covers* which are crimped in over the primer itself.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Those small covers are not noticeable, but do provide a second effective protection against accidental primer percussion inside the Lebel's tube magazine.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Wartime experiences (1914–1918) involving hundreds of millions of Lebel rounds fired in combat have entirely confirmed the effectiveness of these protections.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] While revolutionary for its time in terms of ballistic performance, the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge had its drawbacks.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11mm Gras rifle cartridge case, it was an odd design, with a thick rim and a rapid double taper.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] This made it more difficult to feed from standard magazine firearms such as the Berthier rifles and the Chauchat machine guns, and is the reason for the distinct curvature in the magazines of those firearms.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The Lebel rifle from which it was fired was also rather outdated by the time *balle D*, let alone the *balle N*, came along.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] A *balle N* round can only be fired from Lebel or Berthier rifles, if the chamber has been reamed to accept the larger neck of the N-type cartridge.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Such weapons are stamped *N* on top of the barrel, just in front of the receiver and behind the rear sight.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The *balle N* ammunition is identifiable by the fact that the bullet, while pointed like the solid-brass *balle D*, is lead-cored and jacketed with soft steel.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] While newly manufactured 8×50mmR Lebel ammunition has become available in the U.S., reloadable cartridge cases can also be produced by reforming .348 Winchester brass.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The 8mm Lebel round produced by Prvi Partizan is of excellent quality and replicates the performance of the original round.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] However, Privi Partizan's *older style* brass cases lack the circular groove around the primer cup, so reloaders use round-nosed or flat-nosed bullets when producing handloads for the tube-magazine Lebel rifles with these cases.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] The older Privi Partizan cases loaded with spire point bullets should only be fired single shot.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] More recently, Privi Partizan manufactured Lebel ammunition with spitzer bullets do incorporate the circular groove at the base, and are safe when stacked in the box-magazine of Berthier rifles and the tubular magazine of Lebel rifles.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] Newer cases with circular groove follow the *balle D* specifications, and shooters may use the magazine for loading.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] 1929 (7.5 French) cartridge was introduced.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/8mm-lebel] This made the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge obsolete, but due to post-World War I financial constraints and political neglect, it was not introduced as a rifle cartridge until the adoption, just before World War II, of the MAS-36 rifle.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The purpose of ammunition is to project a force against a selected target to have an effect (usually, but not always, lethal).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] An example of ammunition is the firearm cartridge, which includes all components required to deliver the weapon's effect in a single package.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Until the 20th century, black powder was the most common propellant used, but it has now been replaced in nearly all cases by modern compounds.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Ammunition comes in a wide range of sizes and types and is often designed to work only with specific weapon systems.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] However, there are internationally recognized standards for certain ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) that enable their use across different weapons and by different users.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] There are also specific types of ammunition that are designed to have a specialized effect on a target, such as armor-piercing shells and tracer ammunition, used only in certain circumstances.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Ammunition is commonly labeled or colored in a specific manner to assist in its identification and to prevent the wrong ammunition types from being used accidentally or inappropriately.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The term *ammunition* dates back to the mid-17th century.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The word comes from the French *la munition*, for the material used for war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] *Ammunition* and *munition* are often used interchangeably, although *munition* now usually refers to the actual weapons system with the ammunition required to operate it.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] In some languages other than English ammunition is still referred to as munition, such as: Dutch ("*munitie*"), French ("*munitions*"), German ("*Munition*"), Italian ("*munizione*") and Portuguese ("*munição*").
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Ammunition design has evolved throughout history as different weapons have been developed and different effects required.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Historically, ammunition was of relatively simple design and build (e.g., sling-shot, stones hurled by catapults), but as weapon designs developed (e.g., rifling) and became more refined, the need for more specialized ammunition increased.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Modern ammunition can vary significantly in quality but is usually manufactured to very high standards.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] For example, ammunition for hunting can be designed to expand inside a target, maximizing the damage inflicted by one round.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Anti-personnel shells are designed to fragment into many pieces and can affect a large area.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Armor-piercing rounds are specially hardened to penetrate armor, while smoke ammunition creates a fog that screens people from view.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] More generic ammunition (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) can often be modified slightly to achieve a more specific effect (e.g., tracer, incendiary), whilst larger explosive rounds can be altered by using different fuzes.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The term *fuze* refers to the detonator of an explosive round or shell.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The spelling is different in British English and American English (fuse/fuze respectively), and they are unrelated to a fuse (electrical).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] A fuse was earlier used to ignite the propellant (e.g., such as on a firework) until the advent of more reliable systems, such as the primer or igniter that is used in most modern ammunition.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The fuze of a weapon can be used to alter how the ammunition works.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] These allow a single ammunition type to be altered to suit the situation it is required for.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] There are many fuze designs, ranging from simple mechanical to complex radar- and barometric-based systems.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Fuzes are typically armed by the acceleration force of firing the projectile and are armed several meters after clearing the weapon's bore.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] This helps to ensure the ammunition is safer to handle when loading into the weapon and reduces the chance of the detonator firing before the ammunition has cleared the weapon.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The propellant is the component of ammunition that is activated inside the weapon and provides the kinetic energy required to move the projectile from the weapon to the target.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] In recent years, compressed gas, magnetic energy, and electrical energy have been used as propellants.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Until the 20th century, gunpowder was the most common propellant in ammunition.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] However, it has since been replaced by a wide range of fast-burning compounds that are more reliable and efficient.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The propellant charge is distinct from the projectile charge, which is activated by the fuze, which causes the ammunition effect (e.g., the exploding of an artillery round).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The cartridge is the container that holds the projectile and propellant.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Not all ammunition types have a cartridge case.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] In its place, a wide range of materials can be used to contain the explosives and parts.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] With some large weapons, the ammunition components are stored separately until loaded into the weapon system for firing.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] With small arms, caseless ammunition can reduce the weight and cost of ammunition and simplify the firing process, increasing the firing rate, but the technology is still maturing and has functional issues.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The projectile is the part of the ammunition that leaves the weapon and affects the target.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] This effect is usually either kinetic (e.g., as with a standard bullet) or explosive.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] An ammunition dump is a military facility for storing live ammunition and explosives to be distributed and used at a later date.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Such a storage facility is extremely hazardous, with a high risk of accidents during unloading, packing, and transferring the ammunition.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] In the event of a fire or explosion, the site and its surrounding area are immediately evacuated, and the stored ammunition is left to detonate completely, with limited firefighting attempts from a safe distance.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] In large facilities, there may be a flooding system to extinguish a fire or prevent an explosion automatically.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Typically, an ammunition dump will have a large buffer zone surrounding it to avoid casualties in the event of an accident.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] There will also be perimeter security measures in place to prevent unauthorized personnel from accessing the area and to guard against potential threats from enemy forces.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] A magazine is a place where a quantity of ammunition or other explosive material is stored temporarily before being used.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The term may be used for a facility that stores large quantities of ammunition, although this is normally referred to as an ammunition dump.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Magazines are typically located in the field for quick access when engaging the enemy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The ammunition storage area on a warship is referred to as the "ship's magazine".
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] On a smaller scale, magazine is also the name given to the ammunition storage and feeding device of a repeating firearm.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Gunpowder must be stored in a dry place (stable room temperature) to keep it usable for at least 10 years.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] It is also recommended to avoid hot places, because friction or heat might ignite a spark and cause an explosion.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The standard weapon of a modern soldier is an assault rifle, which, like other small arms, uses cartridge ammunition sized for the weapon.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Ammunition is carried on the person in box magazines specific to the weapon, ammunition boxes, pouches, or bandoliers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The amount of ammunition carried depends on the soldier's strength, the expected action required, and the ammunition's ability to move through the logistical chain to replenish the supply.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] A soldier may also carry a smaller amount of specialized ammunition for heavier weapons, such as machine guns and mortars, thereby spreading the burden of squad weapons among many people.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Too little ammunition threatens the mission, while too much limits the soldier's mobility and also threatens the mission.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] A shell is a payload-carrying projectile which, as opposed to a shot, contains explosives or other fillings, in use since the 19th century.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Artillery shells are ammunition that is designed to be fired from artillery, which has an effect over long distances, usually indirectly (i.e., out of sight of the target).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] There are many different types of artillery ammunition, but they are usually high-explosive and designed to shatter into fragments on impact to maximize damage.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The fuze on an artillery shell can alter how it explodes or behaves, giving it a more specialized effect.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Common types of artillery ammunition include high explosive, smoke, illumination, and practice rounds.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Some artillery rounds are designed as cluster munitions.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Artillery ammunition will almost always include a projectile (the only exception being demonstration or blank rounds), fuze, and propellant of some form.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] When a cartridge case is not used, another method of containing the propellant bags is used, usually in a breech-loading weapon; see Breechloader.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Tank ammunition was developed in World War I as tanks first appeared on the battlefield.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The development of shaped charges has had a significant impact on anti-tank ammunition design, now common in both tank-fired ammunition and in anti-tank missiles, including anti-tank guided missiles.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Naval weapons were originally the same as many land-based weapons, but the ammunition was designed for specific use, such as a solid shot designed to hole an enemy ship and chain-shot to cut rigging and sails.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Modern naval engagements have occurred over far longer distances than historic battles, so as ship armor has increased in strength and thickness, the ammunition to defeat it has also changed.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Naval ammunition is now designed to reach very high velocities (to improve its armor-piercing abilities) and may have specialized fuzes to defeat specific types of vessels.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] However, due to the extended ranges at which modern naval combat may occur, guided missiles have largely supplanted guns and shells.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] With every successive improvement in military arms, a corresponding change has occurred in the method of supplying ammunition in the required quantities.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] As soon as projectiles were required (such as javelins and arrows), there needed to be a method of replenishment.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] When non-specialized, interchangeable, or recoverable ammunition was used (e.g., arrows), it was possible to pick up spent arrows (both friendly and enemy) and reuse them.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] However, with the advent of explosive or non-recoverable ammunition, this was no longer possible, and new ammunition supplies would be needed.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The weight of ammunition required, particularly for artillery shells, can be considerable, necessitating extra time to replenish supplies.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] In modern times, there has been an increase in the standardization of many ammunition types among allies (e.g., the NATO Standardization Agreement) that has enabled the sharing of ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] As of 2013, lead-based ammunition production is the second-largest annual use of lead in the US, accounting for over 60,000 metric tons consumed in 2012.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Lead bullets that miss their target or remain in a carcass or body that was never retrieved can enter environmental systems and become toxic to wildlife.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] The US military has experimented with replacing lead with copper as a slug in their green bullets which reduces the dangers posed by lead in the environment as a result of artillery.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Since 2010, this has eliminated over 2000 tons of lead in waste streams.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Hunters are also encouraged to use monolithic bullets, which exclude any lead content.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/ammunition] Unexploded ammunition can remain active for a very long time and poses a significant threat to both humans and the environment.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] Antony Preston was born in 1938 in Salford, Lancashire, son of the 16th Viscount Gormanston and Miss Julia O'Mahony.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] After becoming a wartime evacuee, he was educated in South Africa at King Edward VII School, Johannesburg, and the University of Witwatersrand.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] On his return to England he spent some years at the National Maritime Museum, Greenwich, before becoming Editor of the periodical *Defence*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] During the 1970s he was employed by a specialist publisher, Conway Maritime Press, as editor of their *Warship* annual.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] He also produced the specialised newsletter *Navint*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] In the early nineties, he took over as chief editor of the magazine *Naval Forces* at the German editorial group Mönch.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] He left to resume as editor of *Warships* in 1996.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] Antony Preston lived in London until his death in 2004.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/antony-preston] His son Matt Preston (born 1961 and the eldest of Preston's four children) has gained celebrity as a TV judge on *MasterChef Australia* and as a restaurant critic-columnist for the Melbourne Age & Herald-Sun newspapers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] Collaborating with Charles Renard, Krebs piloted the first fully controlled free-flight made in the French Army airship *La France*, which was designed in 1884.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight covered 8 km (5.0 mi) in 23 minutes.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight landed back at its starting point.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] On its seven flights the *La France* dirigible returned five times to its starting point.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs and Renard shared the 1886 Ponti prize of the French *Académie des sciences* for their contribution to aerostation.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In Verne's 1886 novel *Robur The Conqueror*, he writes of "the striking experiments of Captain Krebs and Captain Renard".
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1888 Krebs and Gustave Zédé designed the first modern French submarine, the *Gymnote*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] The submarine was fitted with the first naval periscope and the first naval electric gyrocompass.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] The latter allowed the *Gymnote* to force a naval block in 1890.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] From 1884 to 1897 Arthur Krebs modernized the *Ville de Paris* fire department; not only its equipment but its organisation as well.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] His work left a lasting impression in this elite corps.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In May 1896 Arthur Krebs patented a new automobile, fitted with an electromagnetic gearbox and a layout of the front wheels which re-centred them when the steering wheel was left alone.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] Today this is known as the Castor angle.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] The Panhard et Levassor company acquired a license to build 500 cars under the name of Clement-Panhard between 1898 and 1902 featuring this innovation.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs succeeded Levassor as Panhard et Levassor's general manager from 1897 to 1916.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] He transformed the Panhard et Levassor Company into one of the largest and most profitable automobile manufacturers before World War I.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1898 Krebs replaced the tiller with an inclined steering wheel for the Panhard et Levassor car he designed for the Paris-Amsterdam race which ran from 7 to 13 July 1898.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] Fernand Charron won that race on a four-cylinder Panhard et Levassor.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] At the end of 1898, C S Rolls introduced the first car in Britain fitted with wheel steering when he imported a 6 hp Panhard et Levassor from France.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1902 Krebs invented the automatic diaphragm carburettor which gave cars continuous power during acceleration by providing a constant air-fuel ratio at all times; this also led to dramatic improvement in fuel economy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1906 Krebs traveled to the United States to plead in the Selden Case, associated with Henry Ford.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] Also, Krebs contributed significantly to improve the Systeme Panhard (engine in front, rear wheel drive) which became universally adopted before World War II.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1909 Krebs became interested in the Knight patent (sleeve valve engine).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] He was also the first person in France to build that type of engine which Panhard et Levassor would produce during the thirty years leading up to World War II.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] He made contributions to automotive racing with his powerful cars and motorboats.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911 Krebs invented the first elastomeric flexible coupling (cf.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] It is known in French as the *Flector* joint.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] This device is still widely used today in industry for power transmission as a *tyre coupling*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck was meant for military and civil purposes.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911, jointly with the Chatillon Co, Krebs designed the *Tracteur Chatillon-Panhard* all-terrain truck.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck had four wheel drive and four wheel steering and many were used during World War I as artillery tractors.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs also utilized his former military membership to supply the French Army with engines and vehicles including the 1904 Genty Armored car, the 1916 St Chamond tank, the Chatillon-Panhard 4x4 truck, and others.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1960, the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) named Krebs Glacier, a glacier flowing west into the head of Charlotte Bay on the west coast of Graham Land in the Antarctic continent, after Krebs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1934, several months before Arthur Krebs's death, he was made a Commandeur of the Legion of Honour for his work in Aeronautics and for his contributions to the automotive industry.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The **Austrian Empire**, officially known as the **Empire of Austria**, was a multinational European great power from 1804 to 1867, created by proclamation out of the realms of the Habsburgs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] During its existence, it was the third most populous nation in Europe after the Russian Empire and the United Kingdom, while geographically, it was the third-largest empire in Europe after the Russian Empire and the First French Empire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The empire was proclaimed by Francis II in 1804 in response to Napoleon's declaration of the First French Empire, unifying all Habsburg possessions under one central government.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] It remained part of the Holy Roman Empire until the latter's dissolution in 1806.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] It continued fighting against Napoleon throughout the Napoleonic Wars, except for a period between 1809 and 1813, when Austria was first allied with Napoleon during the invasion of Russia and later neutral during the first few weeks of the Sixth Coalition War.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Austria and its allies emerged victorious in the war, leading to the Congress of Vienna, which reaffirmed the empire as one of the great powers of the 19th century.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Kingdom of Hungary—as Regnum Independens—was administered by its own institutions separately from the rest of the empire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] After Austria was defeated in the Austro-Prussian War of 1866, the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 was adopted, joining the Kingdom of Hungary and the Empire of Austria to form Austria-Hungary.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The background of the Austrian Empire is deeply rooted in the gradual rise and consolidation of the Habsburg monarchy, which developed over centuries as one of Europe's most powerful and enduring dynastic systems.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] By the 16th century, they controlled not only the Austrian hereditary lands but also territories such as Bohemia and Hungary, forming a loose but extensive composite monarchy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Rather than being a unified state, the Habsburg monarchy functioned as a collection of distinct regions, each with its own laws, elites, and traditions, all held together by loyalty to the ruling dynasty.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This structure made governance complex, especially as the monarchy encompassed a wide range of ethnic groups, languages, and religions.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Habsburgs also became deeply tied to the Holy Roman Empire, with many of its rulers serving as emperors for centuries.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Religious conflict and external threats further shaped the monarchy's development.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] During the Reformation and Counter-Reformation, the Habsburgs positioned themselves as staunch defenders of Catholicism, which influenced both domestic policies and international alliances.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] At the same time, they faced persistent military pressure from the Ottoman Empire, particularly in Hungary and the Balkans.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] These conflicts pushed the monarchy toward greater centralization and military reform, especially from the 17th century onward.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] By the 18th century, under rulers like Maria Theresa and Joseph II, the monarchy underwent significant administrative and institutional changes.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] These reforms aimed to strengthen central authority, modernize the state, and improve efficiency, though they often met resistance from local elites.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Despite these efforts, the monarchy remained a patchwork of territories rather than a cohesive nation.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This long dynastic, multi-ethnic, and decentralized background is what ultimately gave shape to the Austrian Empire in 1804.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The empire was less a new creation and more a formal rebranding of the Habsburg Monarchy under changing geopolitical pressures, especially in response to the transformations brought by Napoleon.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Changes shaping the nature of the Holy Roman Empire took place during conferences in Rastatt (1797–1799) and Regensburg (1801–1803).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] On 24 March 1803, the Imperial Recess (German: *Reichsdeputationshauptschluss*) was declared, which reduced the number of ecclesiastical states from 81 to only 3 and the free imperial cities from 51 to 6.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Taking this significant change into consideration, Holy Roman Emperor Francis II created the title Emperor of Austria for himself and his successors, thereby becoming Francis I of Austria.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Initially Francis II/I continued to hold both titles but abdicated the throne of the Holy Roman Empire in 1806.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] '*Kaiser*-dom') comprised all the lands of the Habsburg monarchy, which had until then been legally separate realms in personal union (a composite monarchy) under Francis and his predecessors.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] By contrast, the Austrian Empire was legally a single state, although the overarching structure and the status of its component lands at first stayed much the same as they had been under the composite monarchy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Hungary's affairs remained administered by its own institutions (King and Diet) as they had been beforehand; thus no Imperial institutions were involved in its government.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The fall and dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire was accelerated by French intervention in the Empire in 1805, with the French defeating Austrian armies at Ulm and Austerlitz, forcing an Austrian-French armistice on 6 December 1806.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Austrian losses encouraged rulers of imperial territories to ally with the French, receive higher titles and assert formal independence in the following days, such as Maximilian IV Joseph of Bavaria, Frederick III of Württemberg and Charles Frederick of Baden.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Francis II agreed to the humiliating Treaty of Pressburg which recognised the rulers' new titles and ceded large territories to Napoleon's German allies and the French satellite Italy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] In practice this meant the dissolution of the long-lived Holy Roman Empire and a reorganization under a Napoleonic model of the German states.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Austrian claims on those German states were renounced without exception.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] On 12 July 1806, the Confederation of the Rhine was established, comprising 16 sovereigns and countries under French influence, *de facto* put an end to the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] On 6 August 1806, Francis proclaimed the dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire, as he did not want Napoleon to succeed him.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] His claims were later settled by the creation of the Kingdom of Hanover which was held by George IV and William IV as Kings of Hanover.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Succession could only be in the male line, so on Queen Victoria's accession to the British throne, her uncle, Ernest Augustus, succeeded as King of Hanover, thus ending the personal union with Great Britain that dated to 1714.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Klemens von Metternich became Foreign Minister in 1809.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] He also held the post of Chancellor of State from 1821 until 1848, under both Francis I and his son Ferdinand I.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The period of 1815–1848 is also referred to as the "Age of Metternich", with Metternich controlling the Habsburg monarchy's foreign policy and having a major influence in European politics.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] He was known for his strong conservative views and approach in politics, with policies strongly against revolution and liberalism.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] In his opinion, liberalism was a form of legalized revolution.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Metternich believed that absolute monarchy was the only proper system of government.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This notion influenced his anti-revolutionary policy to ensure the continuation of the Habsburg monarchy in Europe.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Metternich was a practitioner of balance-of-power diplomacy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] His foreign policy aimed to maintain international political equilibrium to preserve the Habsburgs' power and influence in international affairs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Following the Napoleonic Wars, Metternich was the chief architect of the Congress of Vienna in 1815.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Austrian Empire was the main beneficiary from the Congress of Vienna and it established an alliance with Britain, Prussia, and Russia forming the Quadruple Alliance.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Austrian Empire also gained new territories from the Congress of Vienna, and its influence expanded to the north through the German Confederation and also into Italy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Due to the Congress of Vienna in 1815, Austria was the leading member of the German Confederation.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Following the Congress, the major European powers agreed to meet and discuss resolutions in the event of future disputes or revolutions.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Because of Metternich's main role in the architecture of the Congress, these meetings are also referred to as the "Metternich congress" or "Metternich system".
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Under Metternich as the Austrian foreign minister, other congresses would meet to resolve European foreign affairs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Metternich congresses aimed to maintain the political equilibrium among the European powers and prevent revolutionary efforts.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] These meetings also aimed to resolve foreign issues and disputes without resorting to violence.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] By means of these meetings and by allying the Austrian Empire with other European powers whose monarchs had a similar interest in preserving conservative political direction, Metternich was able to establish the Austrian Empire's influence on European politics.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Also, because Metternich used the fear of revolutions among European powers, which he also shared, he was able to establish security and predominance of the Habsburgs in Europe.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Under Metternich, nationalist revolts in Austrian north Italy and in the German states were forcibly crushed.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] At home, he pursued a similar policy to suppress revolutionary and liberal ideals.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] He employed the Carlsbad Decrees of 1819, which used strict censorship of education, press and speech to repress revolutionary and liberal concepts.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Metternich also used a wide-ranging spy network to dampen down unrest.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Metternich operated very freely with regard to foreign policy under Emperor Francis I's reign.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This date marks the decline of Metternich's influence in the Austrian Empire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Francis' heir was his son Ferdinand I, but he suffered from health issues.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Ferdinand's accession preserved the Habsburg dynastic succession, but he was not capable of ruling.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The leadership of the Austrian Empire was transferred to a state council composed of Metternich, Francis I's brother Archduke Louis, and Count Franz Anton Kolowrat, who later became the first Minister-President of the Austrian Empire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The liberal Revolutions of 1848 in the Austrian Empire forced Metternich's resignation.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Metternich is remembered for his success in maintaining the status quo and the Habsburg influence in international affairs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] No Habsburg foreign minister following Metternich held a similar position within the empire for such a long time nor held such a vast influence on European foreign affairs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Historians generally consider the Metternich era as a period of stability: the Austrian Empire fought no wars nor did it undergo any radical internal reforms.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] However, it was also thought of as a period of economic growth and prosperity in the Austrian Empire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The population of Austria rose to 37.5 million by 1843.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Urban expansion also occurred and the population of Vienna reached 400,000.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] During the Metternich era, the Austrian Empire also maintained a stable economy and reached an almost balanced budget, despite having a major deficit following the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] From March 1848 through November 1849, the Empire was threatened by revolutionary movements, most of which were of a nationalist character.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Besides that, liberal and even socialist currents resisted the empire's longstanding conservatism.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Although most of the revolution plans failed, some changes were made; significant lasting reforms included the abolition of serfdom, cancellation of censorship and a promise made by Ferdinand I of Austria said to implement a constitution throughout the whole Empire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] After the death of Prince Felix of Schwarzenberg in 1852, the Minister of the Interior Baron Alexander von Bach largely dictated policy in Austria and Hungary.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Bach centralized administrative authority for the Austrian Empire, but he also endorsed reactionary policies that reduced freedom of the press and abandoned public trials.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] He later represented the Absolutist (or *Klerikalabsolutist*) party, which culminated in the concordat of August 1855 that gave the Roman Catholic Church control over education and family life.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This period in the history of the Austrian Empire would become known as the era of neo-absolutism, or Bach's absolutism.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The pillars of the so-called Bach system (*Bachsches System*) were, in the words of Adolf Fischhof, four "armies": *a standing army of soldiers, a sitting army of office holders, a kneeling army of priests and a fawning army of sneaks*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Prisons were full of political prisoners, like Czech nationalist journalist and writer Karel Havlíček Borovský who was forcibly expatriated (1851–1855) to Brixen.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This exile undermined Borovský's health and he died soon afterwards.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This affair earned Bach a very bad reputation among Czechs and subsequently led to the strengthening of the Czech national movement.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] However, Bach's relaxed ideological views (apart from the neo-absolutism) led to a great rise in the 1850s of economic freedom.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Internal customs duties were abolished, and peasants were emancipated from their feudal obligations.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] In its capacity as leader of the German Confederation, Austria participated with volunteers in the First War of Schleswig (1848–1850).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Sardinia allied itself with France for the conquest of Lombardy–Venetia.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Austria was defeated in the 1859 armed conflict.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Treaties of Villafranca and Zürich removed Lombardy, except for the part east of the Mincio river, the so-called Mantovano.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Constitution of 1861 (the "February Patent") created a House of Lords (*Herrenhaus*) and a House of Deputies (*Abgeordnetenhaus*).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] But most nationalities of the monarchy remained dissatisfied.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] After the second war with Denmark in 1864, Holstein came under Austrian administration, and Schleswig and Lauenburg under Prussian administration.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] But the internal difficulties continued.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Diets replaced the parliament in 17 provinces, the Hungarians pressed for autonomy, and Venetia was attracted by the now unified Italy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] After the Austrian army was defeated in the Austro-Prussian War of 1866 and the German Confederation was dissolved, the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 was adopted.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] By this act, the Kingdom of Hungary and the Empire of Austria as two separate entities joined on an equal basis to form the Dual Monarchy of Austria-Hungary.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Napoleonic Wars dominated Austrian foreign policy from 1804 to 1815.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Austrian army was one of the most formidable forces the French had to face.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] After Prussia signed a peace treaty with France on 5 April 1795, Austria was forced to carry the main burden of war with Napoleonic France for almost ten years.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This severely overburdened the Austrian economy, making the war greatly unpopular.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Emperor Francis I therefore refused to join any further war against Napoleon for a long time.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] On the other hand, Francis I continued to intrigue for the possibility of revenge against France, entering into a secret military agreement with the Russian Empire in November 1804.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] This convention was to assure mutual cooperation in the case of a new war against France.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Austrian unwillingness to join the Third Coalition was overcome by British subsidies, but the Austrians withdrew from the war yet again after a decisive defeat at the Battle of Austerlitz.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Although the Austrian budget suffered from wartime expenditures and its international position was significantly undermined, the humiliating Treaty of Pressburg provided plenty of time to strengthen the army and economy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Moreover, the ambitious Archduke Charles and Johann Philipp von Stadion never abandoned the goal of further war with France.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Archduke Charles of Austria served as the Head of the Council of War and Commander in Chief of the Austrian army.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Endowed with the enlarged powers, he reformed the Austrian Army to preparedness for another war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Johann Philipp von Stadion, the foreign minister, personally hated Napoleon due to an experience of confiscation of his possessions in France by Napoleon.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] In addition, the third wife of Francis I, Maria Ludovika of Austria-Este, agreed with Stadion's efforts to begin a new war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Klemens Wenzel von Metternich, located in Paris, called for careful advance in the case of the war against France.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The defeat of French army at the Battle of Bailén in Spain on 27 July 1808 triggered the war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] On 9 April 1809, an Austrian force of 170,000 men attacked Bavaria.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] It participated in a second invasion of France in 1815, and put an end to Murat's regime in south Italy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The latter period of Napoleonic Wars featured Metternich exerting a large degree of influence over foreign policy in the Austrian Empire, a matter nominally decided by the Emperor.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Metternich initially supported an alliance with France, arranging the marriage between Napoleon and Francis I's daughter, Marie-Louise; however, by the 1812 campaign, he had realised the inevitability of Napoleon's downfall and took Austria to war against France.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Metternich's influence at the Congress of Vienna was remarkable, and he became not only the premier statesman in Europe but the virtual ruler of the Empire until 1848—the Year of revolutions—and the rise of liberalism equated to his political downfall.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The result was that the Austrian Empire was seen as one of the great powers after 1815, but also as a reactionary force and an obstacle to national aspirations in Italy and Germany.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] During this time, Metternich was able to maintain an elaborate balance between Prussia, the lesser German states, and Austria in the German Confederation.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Thanks to his efforts, Austria was seen as the senior partner with Prussia keeping watch over Germany as a whole.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Further, Metternich opposed the weakening of France in the years after Napoleon, and viewed the new monarchy in Paris as an effective tool in keeping Russia at bay.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] From 1815 to 1848, Metternich steered Austria Imperial foreign policy, and indeed the mood of Europe, and managed to keep peace on the continent despite the growing liberal and radical movements inside most major powers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] His resignation in 1848, forced by moderates in the court, and revolutionaries in the streets, may have caused the spread of the revolutions throughout the monarchy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] It is stipulated that Metternich's departure emboldened liberal factions in Austria and Hungary, but this cannot be confirmed for certain.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] During the Crimean War, Austria maintained a policy of hostile neutrality towards Russia, and, while not going to war, was supportive of the Anglo-French coalition.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The old Habsburg possessions of Further Austria (in today's France, Germany and Switzerland) had already been lost in the 1805 Peace of Pressburg.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] From 1850, Croatia, Slavonia, and the Military Frontier constituted a single land with disaggregated provincial and military administration, and representation.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Administratively, most of the crown lands excluding Hungary, Croatia, Slavonia, Transylvania, Lombardy–Venetia and the Military Frontier were divided into *Kreise* ('circles'), an administrative division introduced under Maria Theresa in the 18th century.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] In the course of the post-1848 reforms Transylvania was also divided into *Kreise* in 1851 (re-divided in 1854); the Voivodeship of Serbia and Banat of Temeschwar was also divided into *Kreise*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] German was the primary language of higher education in the empire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Austrian foreign trade was one-third of that of France and one-fifth of Great Britain based on 1823–37 numbers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Austrian Empire was multi-national and multi-ethnic, with Germans, Hungarians (constituent in the Kingdom of Hungary), Slavs (Czechs, Poles, Ruthenians, Croats, Slovaks, Serbs, Slovenes) and Romanians, with smaller numbers of other ethnic groups.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Becher's statistics, the population number was 36,950,401 in 1840.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Slavs made up an estimated 16 million, roughly 12 million north of the Danube and 4 million south of it.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Germans made up an estimated 6,5 million, of which 3 million in Upper and Lower Austria, Tyrol and one-half of Styra, and the rest scattered in the other provinces.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Hungarians made up an estimated 5,5 million.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Italians made up an estimated 4,6 million, in Lombardy, Venice, south Tyrol, and south Illyria.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] Wallachians made up an estimated 1,560,000 in Hungary and Transylvania.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] In the mid-19th-century ethnographic works used the term *nationalität* (nationality) as a synonym for *volk* (ethnic group).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The various terms used for the peoples of the monarchy were *Nation*, *Volk*, *Völkerschaft* and derivations *Volkstamm*, *Volksgruppe*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] The Revolutions of 1848 in the Austrian Empire included the minorities choosing sides between revolution against the monarchy or supporting the monarchy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/austrian-empire] When Hungary revolted, the kingdom's Croats, Serbs and Romanians supported the monarchy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] A **battleship** is a large, heavily armored warship with a main battery consisting of large guns, designed to serve as a capital ship.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] From their advent in the late 1880s, battleships were among the largest and most formidable warship types ever built, until they were surpassed by aircraft carriers beginning in the 1940s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The modern battleship traces its origin to the sailing ship of the line, which was developed into the steam ship of the line and soon thereafter the ironclad warship.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] After a period of extensive experimentation in the 1870s and 1880s, ironclad design was largely standardized by the British *Royal Sovereign* class, which are usually referred to as the first "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] These ships carried an armament that usually included four large guns and several medium-caliber guns that were to be used against enemy battleships, and numerous small guns for self-defense.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Naval powers around the world built dozens of pre-dreadnoughts in the 1890s and early 1900s, though they saw relatively little combat; only two major wars were fought during the period that included pre-dreadnought battles: the Spanish–American War in 1898 and the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The following year, the British launched the revolutionary all-big-gun battleship HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This ship discarded the medium-caliber guns in exchange for a uniform armament of ten large guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] All other major navies quickly began (or had already started) "dreadnoughts" of their own, leading to a major naval arms race.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] During World War I, only one major fleet engagement took place: the Battle of Jutland in 1916, but neither side was able to achieve a decisive result.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the Interwar period, the major naval powers concluded a series of agreements beginning with the Washington Naval Treaty that imposed limits on battleship building to stop a renewed arms race.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] During this period, relatively few battleships were built, but advances in technology led to the maturation of the fast battleship concept, and several of these ships were built in the 1930s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The treaty system eventually broke down after Japan refused to sign the Second London Naval Treaty in 1936.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Although the rise of the aircraft carrier during World War II largely relegated battleships to secondary duties, they still saw significant action during that conflict.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Notable engagements include the battles of Cape Spartivento and Cape Matapan in 1940 and 1941, respectively; the sortie by the German battleship *Bismarck* in 1941; the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in 1942; and the Battle of Leyte Gulf in 1944.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] After World War II, most battleships were placed in reserve, broken up, or used as target ships, and few saw significant active service during the Cold War.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The four American *Iowa*-class battleships were reactivated during the Korean War in the early 1950s and again in the 1980s as part of the 600-ship Navy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Even at the height of their dominance of naval combat, some strategists questioned the usefulness of battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Beginning in the mid-1880s, the *Jeune École* (Young School) argued that construction of expensive capital ships should stop in favor of cheap cruisers and torpedo boats.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Despite a period of popularity for the *Jeune École*, the idea fell out of favor and the battleship remained the arbiter of naval combat until World War II.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Even afterward, they remained potent symbols of a country's might and they retained significant psychological and diplomatic effects.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] A number of battleships—predominantly American—remain as museum ships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] A ship of the line was a large, unarmored wooden sailing ship which mounted a battery of up to 120 smoothbore guns and carronades, which came to prominence with the adoption of line of battle tactics in the early 17th century.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] From 1794, the alternative term 'line of battle ship' was contracted to 'battle ship' or 'battleship'.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The sheer number of guns fired broadside meant a ship of the line could wreck any wooden enemy, holing her hull, knocking down masts, wrecking her rigging, and killing her crew.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] They also imparted a psychological effect on the crews of smaller vessels.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Ships of the line were also fairly resilient to the guns of the day; for example, the British Royal Navy lost no first-rate (the largest type of ship of the line) to enemy action during the entire 18th century.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Over time, ships of the line gradually became larger and carried more guns, but otherwise remained quite similar.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Development of the first-rates was particularly conservative, as these ships represented a major investment.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By the early 1800s, the traditional "seventy-four" (so-named because it carried 74 guns) was no longer considered to be a proper ship of the line, having been supplanted by 84- and 120-gun ships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The first major change to the ship of the line concept was the introduction of steam power as an auxiliary propulsion system.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Steam power was gradually introduced to the navy in the first half of the 19th century, initially for small craft and later for frigates.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Early vessels used paddle wheels for propulsion, but by the 1840s, the first screw propeller equipped vessels began to appear.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The value of these smaller steam-powered warships demonstrated their worth, when vessels like the British *Nemesis* proved to be critical to the Anglo-French success in the First Opium War in the 1840s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The French Navy introduced steam to the line of battle with the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850—the first true steam battleship.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] *Napoléon*, which was designed by Henri Dupuy de Lôme, was armed as a conventional ship-of-the-line, but her steam engines could give her a speed of 12 knots (22 km/h; 14 mph), regardless of the wind.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This was a potentially decisive advantage in a naval engagement.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The introduction of steam accelerated the growth in size of battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] France and the United Kingdom were the only countries to develop fleets of wooden, steam-screw battleships although several other navies operated small numbers of screw battleships, including Russia (9), the Ottoman Empire (3), Sweden (2), Naples (1), Denmark (1) and Austria (1).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Concurrent with the development of steam power, another major technological step heralded the end of the traditional ship of the line: guns capable of firing explosive shells.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Pioneering work was done by the French artillery officer Henri-Joseph Paixhans beginning in 1809.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The American artillerist George Bomford followed not far behind, designing the first shell-firing Columbiad in 1812.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The British and Russians began to follow suit in the 1830s, though early smoothbore guns could not fire shells as far as solid shot, which hampered widespread adoption in any fleet.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By the early 1840s, the French Paixhans gun and American Dahlgren gun had begun to be adopted by their respective navies.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the Crimean War of 1853–1855, six Russian ships of the line and two frigates of the Black Sea Fleet destroyed seven Turkish frigates and three corvettes with explosive shells at the Battle of Sinop in 1853.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The battle was widely seen as vindication of the shell gun.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Despite losing her bowsprit and her foremast, and being set on fire, she was ready for action again the very next day.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] As amply demonstrated at the Battle of Sinop, and again during the Anglo-French blockade of Sevastopol from 1854 to 1855, wooden ships had become vulnerable to shell-firing guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This prompted the French emperor Napoleon III to order the first ironclad warships: the *Dévastation*-class ironclad floating batterys.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Three of these ships led the Anglo-French attack on the Russian fortress on the Kinburn Peninsula in the Battle of Kinburn in 1855, where they bore the brunt of Russian artillery fire, but were not seriously damaged.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The success of these ships prompted the French and British to order several similar vessels.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In March 1858, the French took development of the ironclad to its next logical step: a proper, ocean-going armored warship.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This vessel, another design by Dupuy de Lome, was *Gloire*, and after her launching in 1859, Napoleon III ordered another five similar ships, which sparked a naval arms race with Britain.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The first French ironclads had the profile of a ship of the line, cut to one deck due to weight considerations.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Although made of wood and reliant on sail for most journeys, *Gloire* and her contemporaries were fitted with screw propellers, and their wooden hulls were protected by a layer of thick iron armor.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Britain responded promptly with *Warrior*, a similar but much larger ironclad with an iron hull.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By the time *Warrior* was completed in 1861, another nine ironclads were under construction in British shipyards, some of which were conversions of screw ships of the line that were already being built.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Spain and Russia ordered ironclads in 1861, as did the United States and rebel Confederate States of America after the start of the American Civil War.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Construction of these large and expensive warships remained controversial until March 1862, when news of the Battle of Hampton Roads, fought between the Union USS *Monitor* and the Confederate CSS *Virginia*, firmly settled debate in favor of even larger construction programs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] From the 1860s to 1880s, navies experimented with the positioning of guns, in turrets, central-batteries, or barbettes; ironclads of the period also prominently used the ram as a principal weapon.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] As steam technology developed, masts were gradually removed from battleship designs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The British Chief Constructor, Edward Reed, produced the *Devastation*-class ironclads in 1869.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] These were mastless turret ships, which adopted twin-screw propulsion and an arrangement of two pairs of 12-inch (305 mm) guns, one fore and one aft of the superstructure, that prefigured the advent of the pre-dreadnought battleship some two decades later.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By the mid-1870s steel was used as a construction material alongside iron and wood.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The French Navy's *Redoutable*, laid down in 1873 and launched in 1876, was a combination central battery and barbette ship, which became the first capital ship in the world to use steel as the principal building material.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The rapid pace of technological developments, particularly in terms of gun capabilities and thickness of armor to combat them, quickly rendered ships obsolescent.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the continuous attempt by gun manufacturers to keep ahead of developments in armor plate, larger and larger guns were fitted to many of the later ironclads.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Some of these, such as the British *Victoria* class, carried guns as large as 16.25 inches (413 mm) in diameter, while the Italian *Duilio*-class ironclads were armed with colossal 17.7-inch (450 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the 1880s, opposition to fleets of large, expensive ironclads arose around the world, but most notably in France, where a group of naval officers led by Admiral Théophile Aube formed the *Jeune École* (Young School).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The theory, which held as one of its core tenets that small, cheap torpedo boats could easily defeat ironclads, was based on combat experience during the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The doctrine also posited that modern steel-hulled cruisers could defeat a more powerful navy by attacking the country's merchant shipping, rather than engage in a direct battle.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The concept proved to be highly influential for several years, shaping the construction programs of France, Germany, Italy, and Austria-Hungary, among others throughout the world.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In 1889, the British government passed the Naval Defence Act 1889, which embarked on a major naval construction program aimed at establishing the so-called two-power standard, whereby the Royal Navy would be stronger than the next two largest navies combined.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The plan saw the construction of the eight *Royal Sovereign*-class battleships, which have been regarded as the first class of battleship that would retrospectively be referred to as "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] These large battleships incorporated a number of major improvements over earlier vessels like the *Devastation*s, including a high freeboard for true ocean-going capability, more extensive armor protection, heavier secondary battery guns, and greater speed.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The ships were armed with four 13.5 in (340 mm) guns in two twin mounts, fore and aft, which established the pattern for subsequent battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] After building a trio of smaller second class battleships intended for the colonial empire, Britain followed with the nine-strong *Majestic*-class battleships in 1893–1895, which improved on the basic *Royal Sovereign* design.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] These ships adopted the 12 in (305 mm) gun, which would become the standard for all subsequent British pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Foreign navies quickly began pre-dreadnoughts of their own; France began *Brennus* in 1889 and Germany laid down four *Brandenburg*-class battleships in 1890.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The United States Navy laid down three *Indiana*-class battleships in 1891, the same year work began on the Russian battleship *Tri Sviatitelia*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Japan ordered the two *Fuji*-class battleships from British yards, to an improved *Royal Sovereign* design, in 1894.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Navy eventually ordered its own pre-dreadnoughts, beginning with the *Habsburg* class in 1899.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] All of these ships carried guns of between 11 and 13.4 in (280 and 340 mm), save the Austro-Hungarian vessels, which, being significantly smaller than the rest, only carried 9.4 in (240 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] They also generally carried a light armament for defense against torpedo boats and other light craft.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Some ships varied from this general pattern, such as the American *Indiana*s, which carried a heavier secondary battery of 8-inch (203 mm) guns, and the German *Brandenburg*s, which had six 11-inch guns for instead of the usual four heavy guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Many of the early French pre-dreadnoughts, such as *Charles Martel*, carried a mixed heavy armament of two 12-inch and two 10.8-inch (274 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnoughts continued the technical innovations of the ironclad throughout the 1890s and early 1900s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Compound armor gave way to much stronger Harvey armor developed in the United States in 1890, which was in turn superseded by the German Krupp armor in 1894.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] As armor became stronger, it could be reduced in thickness considerably, which saved weight that could be allocated to other aspects of the ship design, and generally permitted larger and more capable battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] At the same time, the advent of smokeless powder continued the trend begun in the French navy of comparatively smaller guns firing at higher velocities.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Early on in the pre-dreadnought era, most navies standardized on the 12-inch gun; only Germany remained the significant outlier, relying on 11-inch and even 9.4-inch guns for its pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Similarly, later in the pre-dreadnought era, the secondary batteries grew in caliber, usually to 7 to 8 in (178 to 203 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the last years of the 19th century and the first years of the 20th, the escalation in the building of battleships became an arms race between Britain and Germany.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The German naval laws of 1890 and 1898 authorized a fleet of 38 battleships, a vital threat to the balance of naval power.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Britain answered with further shipbuilding, but by the end of the pre-dreadnought era, British supremacy at sea had markedly weakened.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In 1883, the United Kingdom had 38 ironclad battleships, twice as many as France and almost as many as the rest of the world put together.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In 1897, Britain's lead was far smaller due to competition from France, Germany, and Russia, as well as the development of pre-dreadnought fleets in Italy, the United States and Japan.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Ottoman Empire, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway, the Netherlands, Chile, and Brazil all had second-rate fleets led by armored cruisers, coastal defence ships or monitors.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnought battleships received their first test in combat in the Spanish–American War in 1898 at the Battle of Santiago de Cuba.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] An American squadron that included four pre-dreadnoughts had blockaded a Spanish squadron of four armored cruisers in Santiago de Cuba until 3 July, when the Spanish ships attempted to break through and escape.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] All four cruisers were destroyed in the ensuing engagement, as were a pair of Spanish destroyers, and the American ships received little damage in return.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The battle seemed to indicate that the mixed batteries of pre-dreadnought battleships were very effective, as the medium-caliber guns had inflicted most of the damage (which reinforced the observations of the Battle of Manila Bay, where only cruisers armed with medium guns had been present).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] It also led navies around the world to begin working on better solutions for rangefinding in the hope of improving gunnery at longer ranges.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Conflicting colonial ambitions in Korea and Manchuria led Russia and Japan to the next major use of pre-dreadnoughts in combat.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] During the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905, squadrons of battleships engaged in a number of battles, including the Battle of the Yellow Sea and the Battle of Tsushima.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Naval mines also proved to be a deadly threat to battleships on both sides, sinking the Russian *Petropavlovsk* in March 1904 and the Japanese battleships *Hatsuse* and *Yashima* on the same day in May.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The action in the Yellow Sea began during a Russian attempt to break out of Port Arthur, which the Japanese under Admiral Tōgō Heihachirō had blockaded.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Russians outmaneuvered the Japanese and briefly escaped, but the latter's superior speed allowed them to catch up.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] A 12-inch shell struck the Russian flagship, killing the squadron commander and causing the Russian ships to fall into disarray and retreat back to Port Arthur.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] With night falling, the Japanese broke off and reimposed the blockade.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] At Tsushima, Togo outmaneuvered the Russian Second Pacific Squadron that had been sent to reinforce the Pacific Fleet, and the Japanese battleships quickly inflicted fatal damage with long-range fire from their 12-inch guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In both actions during the Russo-Japanese War, the fleets engaged at longer range (as far as 12,000 yd (11,000 m) at the Yellow Sea), where only their 12-inch guns were effective.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Only in the final stages of the battle at Tsushima, by which time the Russian fleet had been severely damaged and most of its modern battleships sunk or disabled, did the Japanese fleet close to effective range of their secondary guns, fighting as close as 2,700 yd (2,500 m).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The actions, particularly the decisive engagement at Tsushima, demonstrated that the lessons taken from the Spanish–American War were incorrect, and that the large-caliber gun should be the only offensive weapon carried by battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the early 1900s, some naval theorists had begun to argue for future battleships to discard the heavy secondary batteries and instead carry only big guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The first prominent example was Vittorio Cuniberti, the chief engineer of the Italian *Regia Marina* (Royal Navy); he published an article in 1903 titled "An Ideal Battleship for the British Navy" in *Jane's Fighting Ships*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Japanese Navy was the first to actually order any of these new ships, beginning with the two *Satsuma*-class battleships in 1904, though due to shortages of 12-inch guns, they were completed with a mix of 12- and 10-inch (254 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By early 1905, Fisher had converted to the 12-inch gun for his proposed new capital ships, and in March that year, the German Navy had decided to build an all-big-gun battleship for the planned *Nassau* class.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The American *South Carolina* class was authorized in 1905, but work did not begin until December 1906.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Though several navies had begun design work on all-big-gun battleships, the first to be completed was the British *Dreadnought*, which had been ordered by Fisher.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] He actually preferred a very large armored cruiser equipped with an all-big-gun armament, which would come to be known as the battlecruiser, and he only included *Dreadnought* in his 1905 construction program to appease naval officers who favored continued battleship building.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Fisher believed that Britain's security against the French and Russian threats would be better guaranteed by squadrons of fast battlecruisers, three of which were laid down in 1906.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Regardless of Fisher's intentions, the rapidly changing strategic calculus invalidated his plans and ensured that when the 1906–1907 program was being debated, Germany would be Britain's primary rival, the Royal Navy chose to build three more dreadnoughts instead of further battlecruisers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Reactions from the other naval powers was immediate; very few pre-dreadnoughts were built afterward, and in the first seven years of the ensuing arms race, all of the major naval powers either had their own dreadnoughts in service or nearing completion.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Of these competitions, the Anglo-German race was the most significant, though others took place, such as the South American contest.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Even naval powers of the second and third rank, such as Spain; Brazil, Chile, and Argentina in South America; and Greece and the Ottoman Empire in the Mediterranean had begun dreadnought programs, either domestically or ordering abroad.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Technological development continued over the decade that followed *Dreadnought*'s launch.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Already by 1910, the British had begun the first of the so-called "super-dreadnoughts" that carried significantly more powerful 13.5-inch (340 mm) guns, all on the centerline.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The United States followed suit in 1911, though increasing the caliber of their guns to 14 inches (356 mm).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] France adopted a 13.4 in (340 mm) gun for its *Bretagne*-class battleships, laid down in 1912.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] That year, Japan laid down the first of its *Fusō*-class battleships, also armed with a 14-inch main battery.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Germans waited until 1913, but skipped directly to 15-inch (381 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By this time, Britain had led the way to the 15-inch gun with the *Queen Elizabeth* class begun in late 1912.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] But more importantly than the increase of caliber, the *Queen Elizabeth*s were the first completely oil-fired battleships and the first fast battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] At around the same time, the United States introduced the next major innovation in battleship design: the all or nothing armor system in the *Nevada* class laid down in 1912.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The heaviest possible armor was used to protect the ship's propulsion machinery and ammunition magazines, but intermediate protection was stripped away from non-essential areas, since this mid-weight armor only served to detonate armor-piercing shells.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By the start of World War I in July 1914, the Royal Navy's Grand Fleet outnumbered the German High Seas Fleet by 21 to 13 in numbers of dreadnought battleships and 4 to 3 in battlecruisers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] And over the course of the war, Britain would add another 14 dreadnoughts, while Germany completed another 6.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] German strategy presumed that Britain would launch an immediate offensive into the southern North Sea, but the British preferred to establish a distant blockade, which very quickly stopped German maritime trade.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Both sides were aware that, because of the greater number of British dreadnoughts, a full fleet engagement would be likely to result in a British victory.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The German strategy was therefore to try to provoke an engagement on their terms: either to induce a part of the Grand Fleet to enter battle alone, or to fight a pitched battle near the German coastline, where friendly minefields, torpedo-boats and submarines could be used to even the odds.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The British fleet commander, Admiral John Jellicoe, refused to be drawn into unfavorable conditions and enforced the blockade at the English Channel and between Scotland and Norway.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the Baltic Sea, Germany found itself in the reverse situation, in an even more lopsided fashion versus its Russian opponent.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Russian Baltic Fleet had only four dreadnoughts at the start of the war, so they adopted a purely defensive approach to guard the capital at Petrograd and the northern flank of the Russian army units fighting on the Eastern Front.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the Mediterranean Sea, Italy initially remained neutral, despite being a member of the Triple Alliance with Germany and Austria-Hungary, leaving the latter to face the French Navy and British Mediterranean Fleet alone.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] After ensuring the French army units in French North Africa were safely convoyed to France, the French fleet sailed to the Adriatic Sea to blockade the Austro-Hungarian fleet, which refused to leave their fortified bases.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The French, like the other major European naval commanders, had failed to consider that their opponents would not concede to engaging in battle on terms unfavorable to them.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Adriatic quickly turned into another stalemate as the threat of Austro-Hungarian mines and submarines prevented a more aggressive employment of the French fleet.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Germans embarked on a number of sweeps into the North Sea and raids on British coastal towns to draw out part of the Grand Fleet, which would be isolated and destroyed.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] These included the raid on Scarborough, Hartlepool and Whitby, where the Germans nearly caught an isolated British battle squadron, but turned away, thinking that it was the entire Grand Fleet.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This strategy ultimately led to the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, the largest clash of battleship fleets.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The first stage of the battle was fought largely by the two sides' battlecruiser squadrons, though the British were supported by four of the *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] After both battleship fleets engaged, the British crossed the Germans' "T" twice, but the latter managed to extricate themselves from the action as darkness fell.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Early on 1 June, the High Seas Fleet had reached port.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the course of the fighting, three British battlecruisers were destroyed, as was one German battlecruiser and the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Numerous cruisers and destroyers were lost on both sides as well.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Germans made two further offensive operations in the months after Jutland.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The first, which led to the inconclusive action of 19 August, saw one German battleship torpedoed by a British submarine and two British cruisers sunk by German U-boats.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This incident convinced the British that the risks posed by submarines were too great to send the Grand Fleet into the southern North Sea, barring exceptional circumstances like a German invasion of Britain.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the second German operation, which took place on 18–19 October, a German cruiser was damaged by a submarine and the Grand Fleet remained in port.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By this time, the Germans were similarly convinced of the futility of their attempts to isolate part of the British fleet, and discontinued such raids.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] They instead turned to unrestricted submarine warfare, which resulted in their battleships being reduced to a supporting force that guarded the U-boat bases.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the Baltic, the Germans made two attempts to capture the islands in the Gulf of Riga.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The first came in August 1915, and in the ensuing Battle of the Gulf of Riga, a pair of German dreadnoughts engaged in an artillery duel at long range with the Russian pre-dreadnought *Slava* guarding the minefields that protected the gulf.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Germans drove off the Russian ship, cleared the minefield, but by the time they entered the gulf, submarines had reportedly arrived.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Unwilling to risk the battleships in the shallow, confined waters of the gulf, the Germans retreated.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The second attempt—Operation Albion—took place in October 1917.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] During the Battle of Moon Sound, another pair of German dreadnoughts damaged *Slava* so badly that she had to be scuttled, and the Germans completed their amphibious assault on the islands.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The modern units of the French and British fleets in the Mediterranean spent much of the war guarding the entrance to the Adriatic, first based at Malta and later moving to Corfu.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] They saw very little action through the war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] For their part, the Italians were content to reinforce the blockading force guarding the Adriatic, as they, too, were unwilling to risk their capital ships in the mine and submarine infested waters of the Austrian Littoral.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Instead, light forces carried out most of the operations.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Meanwhile, several French and British pre-dreadnoughts were sent to attack the Ottoman defenses guarding the Dardanelles.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the ensuing naval operations from February to March 1915, several battleships were sunk or damaged by mines and torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] When the fleets failed to break through the defenses, the British and French decided to land at Gallipoli to try to take the fortifications by land; the remaining battleships were thereafter used to provide naval gunfire support.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This, too, ultimately failed and by January 1916, the British and French withdrew their troops.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Russian battleships saw more action in the Black Sea against their Ottoman opponents.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By 1916, the Russians had completed a pair of dreadnoughts in the Black Sea, which severely curtailed Ottoman freedom of maneuver.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the course of the war, older pre-dreadnoughts proved to be highly vulnerable to underwater damage, whether by naval mine or ship-launched or submarine-delivered torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] HMS *Formidable* was sunk by a German U-boat in the English Channel in 1915.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] At the Dardanelles, HMS *Majestic* was sunk by a German U-boat, HMS *Goliath* was sunk by the Ottoman destroyer *Muavenet-i Milliye*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The British *Ocean* and *Irresistible* and the French *Bouvet* were all sunk by mines.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] HMS *Russell* and HMS *Cornwallis* were both sunk by mines in the Mediterranean in 1916 and 1917, respectively.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] HMS *King Edward VII* was similarly mined and sunk off the British coast in 1916, and HMS *Britannia* was sunk by a U-boat in the final days of the war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The French *Gaulois* and *Suffren* were sunk by U-boats in 1916, and *Danton* was torpedoed and sunk by a U-boat in 1917.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] At Jutland, the only battleship lost was the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*, which was torpedoed by a destroyer.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In contrast, dreadnoughts proved to be much more resilient to underwater attack.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] HMS *Marlborough* was damaged by a torpedo at Jutland, but nevertheless returned to port.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The German SMS *Westfalen* was torpedoed at the action of 19 August 1916, and SMS *Grosser Kurfürst* and *Kronprinz* were torpedoed by the same submarine in November 1917; all three survived.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] SMS *Bayern* was mined during Operation Albion and remained in action against Russian artillery batteries for some time thereafter.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Dreadnoughts lost to underwater attack were rare.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] HMS *Audacious* was sunk by a mine in October 1914, the Austro-Hungarian SMS *Szent Istvan* was sunk by Italian MAS boats in June 1918, and five months later, Italian frogmen sank *Viribus Unitis* using a powerful limpet mine.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the immediate aftermath of the war, the most modern units of the German fleet was interned at Scapa Flow, where in June 1919, their crews scuttled the fleet to avoid it being handed over to the Allies.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The remaining dreadnoughts still in German ports were therefore seized as compensation for the scuttled ships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The postwar *Reichsmarine* of Weimar Germany was limited to a contingent of eight old pre-dreadnoughts (of which two would be kept in reserve) under the terms of the Treaty of Versailles; new battleships were subject to severe restrictions on size and armament.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The surviving battleships of Austria-Hungary, the other defeated Central Power, were soon distributed among the Allies, to be broken up.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] While the other major naval powers remained free to build new battleships, most of them were financially crippled after the war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The prospect of a renewed naval arms race between the United States, United Kingdom, and Japan, appealed to few politicians in the three countries, and so they concluded the Washington Naval Treaty in 1922, which also included Italy and France.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The treaty limited the number and size of battleships, and imposed a ten-year building holiday, along with other provisions.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The treaty also imposed a ratio of 5:5:3 on total displacement of battleships for the US, UK, and Japan, respectively, and it severed the Anglo-Japanese Alliance.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The only exceptions to the building holiday were for the two British *Nelson*-class battleships, which were permitted to give Britain parity with the latest American and Japanese battleships, which were all armed with 16-inch (406 mm) guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Washington treaty was followed by a series of other naval treaties, including the First London Naval Treaty (1930) and the Second London Naval Treaty (1936), which both set additional limits on major warships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The treaty limitations meant that fewer new battleships were launched in 1919–1939 than in 1905–1914.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The treaties also inhibited development by imposing upper limits on the weights of ships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Designs like the projected British N3-class battleship, the first American *South Dakota* class, and the Japanese *Kii* class—all of which continued the trend to larger ships with bigger guns and thicker armor—never got off the drawing board.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Those designs which were commissioned during this period were referred to as treaty battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The collapse of the treaty system began during the negotiations for the Second London Treaty, where Japan demanded parity with Britain and the US, which the latter two flatly rejected.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Japan withdrew from the treaty system in 1936, though the agreements remained in effect until January 1937.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] As early as 1914, the British Admiral Percy Scott predicted that battleships would soon be made irrelevant by aircraft.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Between 1916 and 1918, US Admiral William Fullam published a series of papers stating that aircraft would become an independent strike arm of the fleet, and argued that the *Lexington*-class battlecruisers then under construction should be converted to aircraft carriers than scrapped.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By the end of World War I, aircraft had successfully adopted the torpedo as a weapon.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In 1921 the Italian general and air theorist Giulio Douhet completed a hugely influential treatise on strategic bombing titled *The Command of the Air*, which foresaw the dominance of air power over conventional military and naval forces.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In 1921, US General Billy Mitchell used the ex-German dreadnought SMS *Ostfriesland* in a series of bombing tests conducted by the Navy and Army.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The test involved a series of attacks on the stationary, unmanned ships using low-level, land-based bombers dropping bombs that ranged from 550 to 2,000 pounds (250 to 910 kg).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] *Ostfriesland* was sunk by the heaviest bombs, though Mitchell broke the rules of the tests and the subsequent report concluded that had the ship been crewed, underway, and firing back at the aircraft, damage control teams aboard *Ostfriesland* could have managed any damage inflicted.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Mitchell and his supporters nevertheless embarked on a public campaign that falsely claimed that *Ostfriesland* was a super-battleship, and the quick sinking proved that battleships were obsolete.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Mitchell would eventually be subjected to a court martial, convicted, and discharged from the Army over his insubordinate tactics.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Naval aviation traces its origin back to the first decade of the 20th century, though early efforts were based on using aircraft to scout for the fleet and help direct gunfire at long range.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] A number of experimental aircraft carriers were employed during World War I, primarily by the Royal Navy, all converted from merchant vessels or existing warships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The US Navy completed its first carrier, USS *Langley*, in 1922.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] But aircraft carriers in the 1920s faced a number of challenges to be overcome: aircraft of the day were short-ranged, which meant the carrier had to be very close to the enemy to be able to launch and then recover a strike, which exposed the carriers to attack.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In addition, the available planes had insufficient power to carry meaningful bomb loads.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Early naval aviators nevertheless pioneered effective tactics like dive bombing during this period.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Because the Washington Treaty system precluded the construction of any new battleships until the early 1930s, the major naval powers began a program of modernization for their most effective battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Britain conducted a series of refits to their *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships through the 1920s, adding anti-torpedo bulges, additional anti-aircraft guns, and aircraft catapults; further refits in the 1930s increased armor protection and further strengthened their anti-aircraft batteries.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The *Revenge*-class battleships were less heavily modified during the period.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The US *Florida*, *Wyoming* class, and *New York* classes received similar treatments in the 1920s, while the *Nevada* and *Pennsylvania* classes received new turbines, additional armor, and more anti-aircraft guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Japanese similarly updated their *Fusō*, *Ise*, and *Nagato*-class battleships, and rebuilt three of the four *Kongō*-class battlecruisers into fast battleships, albeit with significantly inferior protection compared to the other ships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] They all also received distinctive pagoda masts.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] *Hiei* was initially disarmed to serve as a training ship under the terms of the Washington Treaty, but was remilitarized in the late 1930s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In the 1930s, all four classes were lengthened and had their propulsion systems improved to increase their speeds.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The French and Italian navies were exempted from the 10-year building holiday, owing to the comparative obsolescence of their battleships; they were permitted to build 70,000 long tons (71,000 t) worth of battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] But the weak economies of both countries led both to defer new construction until Germany began building the *Deutschland* class of heavily armed cruiser at the end of the 1920s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This prompted the French to build the *Dunkerque* class of small, fast battleships armed with 13 in (330 mm) guns, which led to a short arms race in Europe in the mid-1930s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Italians responded with the significantly larger and more powerful *Littorio* class, armed with 15-inch guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The French, in turn, began the *Richelieu*-class battleships to counter the *Littorio*s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] By this time, Nazi Germany had signed the Anglo-German Naval Agreement in 1935, which removed the restrictions imposed by Versailles and pegged German naval strength to 35% of British tonnage.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] This permitted the construction of two *Scharnhorst*-class battleships, which were also a response to the *Dunkerque*s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The advent of the *Richelieu*s prompted the Germans to build the two *Bismarck*-class battleships late in the decade.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The Germans thereafter embarked on the ambitious Plan Z naval construction program, which included a total of eight battleships, of which the *Bismarck*s would be the first two.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] Against the backdrop of European rearmament in the mid-1930s, Britain began planning its first battleship class in a decade: the *King George V* class.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] These were armed with 14-inch guns intended to comply with the terms of the Second London Naval Conference, and they were laid down in 1937.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] The United States began their *North Carolina* class at the same time, and though they were intended to be armed with 14-inch guns, Japan's refusal to agree to the Second London Treaty led the US to invoke a clause of the treaty that allowed an increase to 16-inch guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] In 1939, these were followed by the four *South Dakota*-class battleships, and in 1940 by the first of four *Iowa*-class battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p01] For its part, Japan had decided to embark on a program of four very large *Yamato*-class battleships, armed with 18-inch (457 mm) guns, as early as 1934, though work did not begin on the first ship until late 1937.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The German pre-dreadnought *Schleswig-Holstein* fired the first shots of World War II by initiating the bombardment of the Polish garrison at Westerplatte in the early hours on 1 September 1939.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The German *Scharnhorst*-class battleships caught the British carrier HMS *Glorious* off the coast of Norway and sank her during the Norwegian campaign.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] In the former action, the British sank a pair of older *Bretagne*-class battleships and the fast battleship *Dunkerque*, though the latter was refloated and repaired.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] At Dakar, the French battleship *Richelieu* and other forces fended off the British task force, which resulted in the torpedoing of the battleship HMS *Resolution*, which was severely damaged.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Italy entered the war in June 1940, shortly before the French defeat.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] In November, the British launched a nighttime airstrike on the naval base at Taranto; in the Battle of Taranto, Fairey Swordfish torpedo bombers disabled three Italian battleships, though they were subsequently repaired.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Over the next year, Italian and British battleships engaged in a number of inconclusive actions as they contested the supply lines to North Africa.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] These included the Battle of Cape Spartivento in November 1940 and the Battle of Cape Matapan in March 1941.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] At Matapan, the battleship *Vittorio Veneto* was badly damaged by a Swordfish, though the ship returned to port.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The British battleships *Valiant*, *Warspite*, and *Barham* nevertheless caught a group of three heavy cruisers that evening and destroyed them in a furious, close-range night action.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Convoy battles continued through 1941 and into 1942, with actions such as First and Second Sirte.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] By 1943, Italian operations were sharply reduced due to a shortage of fuel, and after the Allied invasion of Italy, the country surrendered, allowing most of its fleet to be interned at Malta.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] While on the way, the battleship *Roma* was sunk by a German Fritz X guided glide bomb.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] In the meantime, in January 1941, the Germans began to send their few battleships on commerce raiding operations in the Atlantic, starting with the two *Scharnhorst*-class ships in Operation Berlin, which was not particularly successful.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Bismarck* followed with Operation Rheinübung in May, which resulted in two actions, the Battle of the Denmark Strait and the sinking of *Bismarck*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] During the operation, *Bismarck* was crippled by Swordfish torpedo bombers, which allowed a pair of British battleships to catch and destroy her.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] By 1942, the last operational German battleships—*Tirpitz* and *Scharnhorst*—were sent to occupied Norway to serve as a fleet in being to tie down British naval resources and to attack supply convoys to the Soviet Union.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The battleship HMS *Duke of York* eventually sank *Scharnhorst* at the Battle of North Cape in December 1943, and *Tirpitz* was destroyed by British heavy bombers in 1944.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] On 7 December 1941, the Japanese launched a surprise attack on the US naval base at Pearl Harbor.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Over the course of two waves of dive-, level- and torpedo bombers, the Japanese sank or destroyed five battleships and inflicted serious damage to the facilities there.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Three days later, land-based Japanese aircraft operating out of French Indochina, then occupied by Japan, caught and sank the British battleship HMS *Prince of Wales* and the battlecruiser HMS *Repulse* off the coast of British Malaya.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Though the Taranto and Pearl Harbor strikes were significant steps toward aircraft replacing the battleship as the primary naval striking arm, the sinking of *Prince of Wales* and *Repulse* marked the first time aircraft had sunk capital ships that were maneuvering and returning fire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Employment of battleships during the Pacific War was limited by a number of factors.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Japanese strategic doctrine, the *Kantai Kessen*, envisioned a decisive clash of battleships at the end of the war, and so kept most of their battleships in home waters, and only the four *Kongō*s were routinely detached to escort the aircraft carriers of the *Kido Butai*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] For their part, the US kept its surviving pre-war battleships out of action primarily because they were too slow to keep up with the carriers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Later in the war, they were employed as coastal bombardment vessels.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Nevertheless, American and Japanese battleships saw significant action during the Guadalcanal campaign in 1942, most notably at the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in November.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] There, an American squadron centered on the battleships *Washington* and *South Dakota* intercepted and sank the battleship *Kirishima*, though *South Dakota* received significant damage in return.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] As more and more of the American fast battleships entered service from 1942, onward, they were frequently used as escorts for the fast carrier task force that was the US Navy's primary striking arm in its campaign across the central Pacific.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] During the Philippines campaign, battleships played a central role during the Battle of Leyte Gulf in October 1944.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The action was one of the largest naval battles in history, which took place over several days and as three Japanese fleets attacked the Allied invasion fleet.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The Japanese battleship *Musashi*, part of Center Force, was sunk by American carrier aircraft during the Battle of Sibuyan Sea on 24 October.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Surigao Strait the following night, several US battleships that had been repaired from the attack on Pearl Harbor defeated the Japanese Southern Force that included a pair of battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Center Force attacked again on 25 October in the Battle off Samar, but was driven off by destroyers and aircraft from several escort carriers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Okinawa in April 1945, Japan sent *Yamato* as a final suicide mission to attack the landing beaches and attempt to stop the invasion of the island.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] American aircraft scored between nine and thirteen torpedo hits and six bomb hits on the ship and sank her.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Haruna* was sunk by US aircraft off Kure, Japan, in July.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The war ended with the Japanese surrender aboard the battleship USS *Missouri* in September 1945.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] After World War II, several navies retained their existing battleships, but most were either placed in their reserve fleets or scrapped outright.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Of their surviving pre-war battleships, most of the American vessels were either scrapped or sunk as target ships by 1948, though the most modern vessels, those of the *Tennessee* and *Maryland* classes, survived until the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] One of the earlier vessels, USS *Texas*, was preserved as a museum ship.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The four *King George V*-class ships were all broken up by 1957, Only two battleships—the British HMS *Vanguard* and the French *Jean Bart*—were completed after the war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Vanguard* did not long outlast the *King George V*s, being scrapped herself in 1960.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Jean Bart* (and her sister *Richelieu*) remained in the French fleet's inventory until the early 1960s, when they were discarded.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Three of the six American *North Carolina*- and *South Dakota*-class ships were similarly scrapped in the early 1960s, but the other three—*North Carolina*, *Massachusetts*, and *Alabama*—were retained as museum ships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] With the reduced naval budgets of the immediate postwar period, the US Navy chose to concentrate its resources on its carrier force.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Besides the rise of aircraft carriers as the preeminent naval striking force, the advent of nuclear weapons influenced the decision to abandon large battleship fleets.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] In 1946, *Nagato*, which was seized by the US, and four American battleships were used during the Operation Crossroads nuclear weapons tests, though three of the American ships survived the two blasts and were later sunk with conventional weapons.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Of the remaining, smaller battleships fleets, Italy retained its two *Andrea Doria*-class battleships, of 1913 vintage, until the late 1950s and early 1960s, when they were scrapped.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] One other battleship, *Giulio Cesare* was taken by the Soviets as reparations and renamed *Novorossiysk*; she was sunk by a mine in the Black Sea on 29 October 1955.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The two surviving *Littorio*-class ships were taken by the US and UK as war reparations and scrapped in the late 1940s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The Soviets still had a pair of World War I-era battleships—*Parizhskaya Kommuna* and *Gangut*—but they, too, were scrapped in the late 1950s.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The three large South American navies still had a handful of pre-World War I dreadnoughts in service after the war.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Brazil eventually discarded its two *Minas Gerais*-class battleships in the early 1950s; *Argentina* sold its two *Rivadavia*-class battleships in 1956; the last ship in the region, the Chilean *Almirante Latorre*, followed them to the breakers' yard in 1959.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The four *Iowa*-class battleships were the only vessels of the type to see significant combat after World War II.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] All four ships were reactivated for gunfire support duties during the Korean War in the early 1950s, and *New Jersey* was also deployed during the Vietnam War in 1968–1969 for the same task.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] All four ships were modernized in the early 1980s with Tomahawk cruise missiles, Harpoon anti-ship missiles, and Phalanx CIWS systems, along with the latest radar systems.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] They were recommissioned as part of the 600-ship Navy program under President Ronald Reagan.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *New Jersey* next saw action in 1982, bombarding Syrian artillery during the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* took part in Operation Desert Storm against Iraqi forces in 1991, bombarding enemy positions along the coast.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The ships proved to be expensive to operate, and they required thousands of men to keep in service, so *Iowa* and *New Jersey* were already back in reserve by that time, and *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* were also decommissioned by the end of 1991.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] All four were struck from the Naval Vessel Register in 1995.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] When the last *Iowa*-class ship was finally stricken from the Naval Vessel Registry, no battleships remained in service or in reserve with any navy worldwide.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] A number are preserved as museum ships, either afloat or in drydock.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The U.S. has eight battleships on display: *Massachusetts*, *North Carolina*, *Alabama*, *Iowa*, *New Jersey*, *Missouri*, *Wisconsin*, and *Texas*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *New Jersey* are museums at Pearl Harbor and Camden, New Jersey, respectively.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Iowa* is on display as an educational attraction at the Los Angeles Waterfront in San Pedro, California.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Wisconsin* now serves as a museum ship in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Massachusetts*, which has the distinction of never having lost a man during service, is on display at the Battleship Cove naval museum in Fall River, Massachusetts.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Texas*, the first battleship turned into a museum, is normally on display at the San Jacinto Battleground State Historic Site, near Houston, but as of 2021 is closed for repairs.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *North Carolina* is on display in Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] *Alabama* is on display in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The USS Arizona Memorial was erected over the wreck of *Arizona*, which was sunk during the Pearl Harbor attack in 1941, to commemorate those killed in the raid.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Memorials were also placed to mark the wreck of *Utah*, also sunk during the attack.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The only other 20th-century battleship on display is the Japanese pre-dreadnought *Mikasa*, preserved since 1923.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] On 22 December 2025, the United States Navy announced the planned construction of new battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The Trump class will be the first nuclear-powered battleship, and it is planned to carry nuclear-capable cruise missiles, and conventional weapons.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] For much of their existence, battleships were the embodiment of sea power.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The American naval officer Alfred Thayer Mahan argued in his seminal 1890 work, *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*, a strong navy was vital to the success of a nation, and control of the seas was a prerequisite for the projection of force.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Conversely, countries with weak navies would inevitably decline.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Mahan argued that the cruiser warfare advocated by the *Jeune Ecole* could never be decisive, and that only fleets of battleships could control sea lanes and enforce blockades of an enemy's coast.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The book proved to be widely influential across the world's navies; it was translated into German in 1896, where it was used to support the German naval expansion program championed by Alfred von Tirpitz.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] A Japanese-language translation also appeared in 1896, and it soon became required reading at the Japanese naval academy.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] By the end of the decade, Russian, French, Italian, and Spanish versions were produced.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The "fleet in being" in part acts as a deterrent against attack.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The concept underpinned Tirpitz's so-called "risk theory" that was the basis of his program to build a German battle fleet.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Even if the Royal Navy maintained a numerical superiority, the risk that the German fleet would inflict grievous damage even in the case of a British victory would militate against any such battle taking place, and Germany would be free to pursue its global ambitions.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, naval tacticians had developed a number of formations in which to employ battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The most prominent were referred to as "line ahead" and "line abreast".
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The former, the standard tactic during the age of sail, arrayed ships in a single-file line, which emphasized broadside fire.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The latter placed ships side-by-side, which was suited to close-range melees where ramming and torpedoes could be effectively employed; after Tegetthoff's success at Lissa in 1866 used a modified line abreast formation, the tactic enjoyed a period of popularity for several years.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] By the 1880s, line-ahead tactics had returned to prominence.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Royal Navy officers devised the tactic referred to as "crossing the T" of an enemy fleet, whereby one fleet steaming in line-ahead formation crossed in front of another line of battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] This maneuver would allow one's own battleships to concentrate entire broadsides on the leading enemy ship, while one's opponent could only reply with their forward guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Many navies adopted the tactic soon thereafter.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] As the threat of underwater attack, including mines and torpedoes, developed after the 1860s, capital ships could no longer maintain close blockades of enemy ports.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] This required smaller, faster scouts to observe hostile ports so that an enemy fleet could be brought to battle.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Modern cruisers began to be built in the 1880s for this purpose.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Almost immediately after the invention of the airplane, navies recognized its potential as a reconnaissance unit for the fleet's battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The Austro-Hungarian Navy, then following the *Jeune École* doctrine of the 1870s and 1880s, devised the tactic of placing torpedo boats alongside battleships; these would hide behind the larger ships until gun-smoke obscured visibility enough for them to dart out and fire their torpedoes.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] While this tactic was made less effective by the development of smokeless propellant, the threat from more capable torpedo craft (later including submarines) remained.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, the Royal Navy had developed the first destroyers, which were initially designed to intercept and drive off any attacking torpedo boats.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The other major naval powers quickly followed suit with similar vessels of their own.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The presence of battleships had a great psychological and diplomatic impact.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Similar to possessing nuclear weapons in the second half of the 20th century, the ownership of battleships marked a country as a regional or global power, and the ability to build them domestically signified that a country could claim to be a great power.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Even during the Cold War, the psychological impact of a battleship was significant.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] In September 1983, when Druze militia in Lebanon's Shouf Mountains fired upon U.S.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Marine peacekeepers, the arrival of USS *New Jersey* stopped the firing.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Gunfire from *New Jersey* later killed militia leaders.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] Battleships were the largest and most complex, and hence the most expensive warships of their time; as a result, the value of investment in battleships has always been contested.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] As the French politician Etienne Lamy wrote in 1879, "The construction of battleships is so costly, their effectiveness so uncertain and of such short duration, that the enterprise of creating an armored fleet seems to leave fruitless the perseverance of a people".
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The *Jeune École* school of thought of the 1870s and 1880s sought alternatives to the crippling expense and debatable utility of a conventional battlefleet.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] It proposed what would nowadays be termed a sea denial strategy, based on fast, long-ranged cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo boat flotillas to attack enemy ships attempting to blockade French ports.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The ideas of the *Jeune École* were ahead of their time; it was not until the 20th century that efficient mines, torpedoes, submarines, and aircraft were available that allowed similar ideas to be effectively implemented.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/battleship-p02] The determination of powers such as Germany to build battlefleets with which to confront much stronger rivals has been criticized by historians, who emphasize the futility of investment in a battlefleet that has no chance of matching its opponent in an actual battle.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] The **Canet guns** were a series of weapon systems developed by Gustave Canet, who worked as an engineer from 1872 to 1881 for the London Ordnance Works, then for Forges et Chantiers de la Méditerranée, and from 1897 to 1907 for Schneider et Cie of Le Creusot.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] Canet developed a 12.6 in (32 cm) 38 cal naval gun, an extremely powerful weapon for its time, specifically for the export market.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] The gun was first selected by the Spanish Navy in 1884 as part of a large naval expansion program which called for six new battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] The Spanish armaments firm Hontoria obtained a manufacturing license to produce the weapon, but due to budgetary reasons, only one vessel, the *Pelayo*, was completed.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] Canet was more successful in sales to the Empire of Japan, when the gun was selected by the French military advisor and naval architect Louis-Émile Bertin as the main battery of the *Matsushima*-class cruiser, new type of cruiser he had designed in 1887.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] The usage was consistent with the Jeune École philosophy, which advocated placing overwhelming firepower (strong guns, torpedoes) on relatively small ships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] This philosophy was of great interest to the Imperial Japanese Navy, which lacked the resources at the time to purchase modern pre-dreadnought battleships.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] The guns supplied to Japan equipped the cruisers *Matsushima*, *Itsukushima*, and *Hashidate*.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] Each gun weighed 67 tons, and had a barrel 12 metres (39 ft) long, firing a 112 cm (44 in) long projectile with weight of 350 kg (770 lb) (or 449 kg (990 lb) high explosive) for an effective range of 8,000 metres (26,000 ft).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] The guns proved only marginally successful during the First Sino-Japanese War, due to a slow rate of fire, and numerous mechanical problems.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] The guns could not be aimed abeam, as their weight would cause the ship to roll over when fired.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] In combat, gunners were able to fire only around one shot per hour due to the time it took to reload.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/canet-guns] Canet is also known for developing the Schneider-Canet gun system for 75 mm iron BL mountain guns, and rapid-fire 120 mm and 152 mm guns.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] Launched in 1850, she was the lead ship of a class of nine battleships, all built over a period of ten years.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] This class of ship was designed by the famous naval designer Henri Dupuy de Lôme.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] The Prince of Joinville mentioned the incident in his *Vieux Souvenirs*, bitterly writing "I still laugh about it".
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] Her success made the steam reconstruction of the fleets of the world a necessity.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] her performances attracted great attention, and the type she represented was largely increased in numbers.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] In her design boldness and prudence were well combined.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] From 1844–45 the Anglo-French Entente collapsed following the French interventions in Tahiti and Morocco, and the publication of French pamphlets advocating a stronger navy (such as "*Notes sur l’état des forces navales*" by the Prince de Joinville), leading to an arms race in the naval area.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] The Royal Navy had also commissioned a number of steam sloops, HMS *Rattler* being the first screw-propelled warship to be launched anywhere in the world in 1843.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] Both nations had also developed steam frigates, the French *Pomone* launched in 1845, and the British *Amphion* a year later.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] However, *Napoléon* was the first regular steam battleship to be launched.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] In 1847, Britain had designed a screw/steam battleship named *James Watt*, but the project much delayed and she did not enter service until 1854.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] Her sister ship, *Agamemnon*, was ordered in 1849 and commissioned in January 1853.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] Another sailing battleship, *Sans Pareil*, was converted to steam on the stocks and launched in March 1851; she beat *Agamemnon* into service in November 1852.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] Britain’s reluctance to commit to the steam battleship apparently stemmed from her commitment to long-distance, worldwide operation, for which, at that time, sail was still the most reliable mode of propulsion.
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] In the end, France and Great Britain were the only two countries to develop fleets of wooden steam battleships, although several other navies are known to have had at least one unit, built or converted with British technical support (Russia, Turkey, Sweden, Naples, Denmark and Austria).
[src:french-ship-napoléon-1850/french-ship-napoléon-1850] Altogether, France built 10 new wooden steam battleships and converted 28 from older battleship units, while Britain built 18 and converted 41.
